{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644871"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:10:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:10:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18071"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.96,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74934"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10785"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60435"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5732"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74934"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMedical ethicists often discuss the concept of \u0027full moral status\u0027 when considering the rights and interests of different entities in healthcare decision-making.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes what it means for an entity to have full moral status?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Has the ability to experience physical pain","Has biological human DNA","Possesses rights and interests that must be respected","Can communicate with healthcare providers","Demonstrates measurable brain activity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that an entity with full moral status \u003Cstrong\u003Epossesses rights and interests that must be respected\u003C/strong\u003E. This means they have inherent value and dignity that creates moral obligations in others to consider and protect their interests.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ehas the ability to experience physical pain\u003C/strong\u003E is relevant to moral consideration, sentience alone is insufficient for full moral status, as many animals can experience pain but may not have full moral status.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas biological human DNA\u003C/strong\u003E does not determine moral status, as what matters are morally relevant characteristics like consciousness and rationality rather than species membership.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECan communicate with healthcare providers\u003C/strong\u003E is not required for full moral status, as demonstrated by infants or unconscious patients who retain full moral status despite being unable to communicate.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Edemonstrates measurable brain activity\u003C/strong\u003E may be relevant to moral status, it is neither necessary nor sufficient as the sole criterion for determining full moral status.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EFull moral status typically requires characteristics such as consciousness, rationality, and the ability to value one\u0027s own existence. These create obligations in others to respect the entity\u0027s rights and interests.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Full moral status means an entity has rights, interests and inherent value that must be respected.","Personhood is often considered the key criterion for full moral status in medical ethics.","Consciousness, rationality, and the ability to value one\u0027s own existence are common requirements for full moral status."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60435"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60435"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T12:24:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T12:25:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10785"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74934"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio